<p>Also, <code>num &lt; x || num &gt; -x</code> is inclusive of all possible numbers, so that’s likely not what you’re intending</p>","post_number":2,"post_type":1,"posts_count":11,"updated_at":"2023-03-24T03:44:31.100Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":1,"reads":114,"readers_count":113,"score":32.8,"yours":false,"topic_id":431549,"topic_slug":"time-based-programming-help","display_username":"Fletch","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":9105,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"3181/3015 Mentor | 213/1373 Alum | CSA/FTAA/Jack-of-all-Trades"},"post_url":"/t/time-based-programming-help/431549/2","custom_user_title":"3181/3015 Mentor | 213/1373 Alum | CSA/FTAA/Jack-of-all-Trades","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3172004,"name":"Jack Allen","username":"Wrench422","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/w/76d3ee/{size}.png","created_at":"2023-03-24T03:58:28.372Z","cooked":"<p>Yes, I have confirmed that getYComplementaryAngle() returns the value I need. The first if statement(that has timer and gyro angle) is supposed to stay on until the gyro reads greater than 14 or less than -14. The second one is supposed to turn on when the gyro reds greater than 14 or less than -14. I think it should be doing that? Although please correct me if I’m mixing something up</p>","post_number":3,"post_type":1,"posts_count":11,"updated_at":"2023-03-24T03:58:28.372Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":2,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":109,"readers_count":108,"score":26.8,"yours":false,"topic_id":431549,"topic_slug":"time-based-programming-help","display_username":"Jack Allen","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"reply_to_user":{"id":9105,"username":"Fletch1373","name":"Fletch","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/fletch1373/{size}/220073_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":53635,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"post_url":"/t/time-based-programming-help/431549/3","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3172008,"name":"Fletch","username":"Fletch1373","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/fletch1373/{size}/220073_2.png","created_at":"2023-03-24T04:07:13.424Z","cooked":"<p>Your first <code>if</code> that checks gyro angle looks like you want to find a value BETWEEN -14 and 14, right? So step through the logic bit by bit using, say, 20.</p>
<details>
<summary>
Spoilers!</summary>
<p>It should be false as its not between, but you’ll find that it actually passes the <code>&gt; -14</code> condition and since you have it OR’d, it will evaluate to true.</p>
<p>What you like want for the 2 conditions is <code>&gt; -14 &amp;&amp; &lt; 14</code> for the first, and <code>&lt; -14 || &gt; 14</code> for the second.</p>
</details>
<p>Edit: I just noticed why you’re not driving reverse.  The classic blunder known as integer division! <code>-1 / 3</code> will not evaluate how youd expect (but <code>-1.0 / 3.0</code> should)</p>","post_number":4,"post_type":1,"posts_count":11,"updated_at":"2023-03-24T04:09:58.673Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":3,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":1,"reads":96,"readers_count":95,"score":29.2,"yours":false,"topic_id":431549,"topic_slug":"time-based-programming-help","display_username":"Fletch","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","reply_to_user":{"id":53635,"username":"Wrench422","name":"Jack Allen","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/w/76d3ee/{size}.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":9105,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"3181/3015 Mentor | 213/1373 Alum | CSA/FTAA/Jack-of-all-Trades"},"post_url":"/t/time-based-programming-help/431549/4","custom_user_title":"3181/3015 Mentor | 213/1373 Alum | CSA/FTAA/Jack-of-all-Trades","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3172009,"name":"Jack Allen","username":"Wrench422","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/w/76d3ee/{size}.png","created_at":"2023-03-24T04:12:13.079Z","cooked":"<p>I understand the gyro and angle bit now! Thanks for that help! And yeah, I found out about integer division too from another source too. Would have been a great thing to know 4 hours ago when I had the robot sitting in front of me! Wouldn’t it be nice if stuff just worked! Thanks for all your help!!</p>","post_number":5,"post_type":1,"posts_count":11,"updated_at":"2023-03-24T04:12:13.079Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":4,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":1,"reads":83,"readers_count":82,"score":41.6,"yours":false,"topic_id":431549,"topic_slug":"time-based-programming-help","display_username":"Jack Allen","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"reply_to_user":{"id":9105,"username":"Fletch1373","name":"Fletch","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/fletch1373/{size}/220073_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":1}],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":53635,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"post_url":"/t/time-based-programming-help/431549/5","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[{"id":"heart","type":"emoji","count":1}],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":1,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3172017,"name":"Fletch","username":"Fletch1373","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/fletch1373/{size}/220073_2.png","created_at":"2023-03-24T04:37:25.830Z","cooked":"<p>Computers will always do what you tell them to do, and EXACTLY what you tell them to do.  Even if you dont realize thats what youre telling them to do…</p>","post_number":6,"post_type":1,"posts_count":11,"updated_at":"2023-03-24T04:37:25.830Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":5,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":76,"readers_count